    <id>http://arxiv.org/abs/2605.15188v1</id>
    <title>FutureSim: Replaying World Events to Evaluate Adaptive Agents</title>
    <updated>2026-05-14T17:59:28Z</updated>
    <link href="https://arxiv.org/abs/2605.15188v1" rel="alternate" type="text/html"/>
    <link href="https://arxiv.org/pdf/2605.15188v1" rel="related" type="application/pdf" title="pdf"/>
    <summary>AI agents are being increasingly deployed in dynamic, open-ended environments that require adapting to new information as it arrives. To efficiently measure this capability for realistic use-cases, we propose building grounded simulations that replay real-world events in the order they occurred. We build FutureSim, where agents forecast world events beyond their knowledge cutoff while interacting with a chronological replay of the world: real news articles arriving and questions resolving over the simulated period. We evaluate frontier agents in their native harness, testing their ability to predict world events over a three-month period from January to March 2026. FutureSim reveals a clear separation in their capabilities, with the best agent's accuracy being 25%, and many having worse Brier skill score than making no prediction at all. Through careful ablations, we show how FutureSim offers a realistic setting to study emerging research directions like long-horizon test-time adaptation, search, memory, and reasoning about uncertainty. Overall, we hope our benchmark design paves the way to measure AI progress on open-ended adaptation spanning long time-horizons in the real world.</summary>
    <category term="cs.LG" scheme="http://arxiv.org/schemas/atom"/>
